Kong Extensions
1. Add Kong Plugins (most impactful for learning)
Apply rate limiting and JWT auth directly on the HTTPRoute or Gateway:


# KongPlugin resource
apiVersion: configuration.konghq.com/v1
kind: KongPlugin
metadata:
  name: rate-limit-payments
plugin: rate-limiting
config:
  minute: 100
  policy: local
Teaches you how Kong middleware works on top of Kubernetes Gateway API.

2. Kong Admin API / Kong Manager UI
Expose Kong's Admin API and install Kong Manager to visualize routes, plugins, and upstreams — useful for debugging and understanding what KIC is configuring under the hood.

3. Key-Auth or JWT per domain
Add authentication at the domain gateway level — each business domain (Payments, GRC, Retail) enforces its own token validation.

Istio Extensions
4. Observability Stack (highest learning value)
Install the Istio addons — this alone teaches a huge amount:


kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/istio/istio/release-1.22/samples/addons/prometheus.yaml
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/istio/istio/release-1.22/samples/addons/grafana.yaml
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/istio/istio/release-1.22/samples/addons/jaeger.yaml
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/istio/istio/release-1.22/samples/addons/kiali.yaml
Kiali will draw your exact service mesh topology. Jaeger shows the full request trace across all 3 hops in each domain chain.

5. Istio AuthorizationPolicy (zero-trust RBAC)
Extends beyond PeerAuthentication — controls which service is allowed to call which service:


apiVersion: security.istio.io/v1
kind: AuthorizationPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-payments-kic-only
  namespace: payments-team
spec:
  action: ALLOW
  rules:
  - from:
    - source:
        principals: ["cluster.local/ns/payments-kic/sa/payments-kic-gateway"]
Teaches the difference between encryption (mTLS) and authorization (RBAC).

6. Fault Injection & Circuit Breaking
Use Istio VirtualService to inject faults and test resilience:


apiVersion: networking.istio.io/v1
kind: VirtualService
metadata:
  name: fx-svc-fault
  namespace: payments-team
spec:
  hosts:
  - fx-svc
  http:
  - fault:
      delay:
        percentage:
          value: 50
        fixedDelay: 3s
    route:
    - destination:
        host: fx-svc
Then add a DestinationRule with outlierDetection to see circuit breaking kick in.

Architecture Extensions
7. Canary / Traffic Splitting
Split traffic between two versions of a service (e.g., transfer-svc-v1 vs transfer-svc-v2) using Istio VirtualService weights — simulates a real deployment strategy.

8. Egress Control
Add an ServiceEntry + egress DestinationRule to control which external APIs your backend services can call. Relevant for a banking context (e.g., controlling outbound calls to payment processors).

9. Horizontal Pod Autoscaler + Load Testing
Add HPA to the backend services, then use k6 or hey to load test through the global gateway — see Kong handle traffic scaling while Istio metrics show the load distribution.

